        <link id="build-style-article" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/products/rsna/releasedAssets/css/build-article-8932601a697666afa607.css"/><article xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" data-design="pill" data-has="right-rail" data-type="research-article" vocab="http://schema.org/" typeof="ScholarlyArticle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><header data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><div data-article-access="no" data-article-access-type="other" class="meta-panel"><div class="meta-panel__left-content"><div class="meta-panel__label"><span>Nuclear Medicine</span></div><div class="meta-panel__onlineDate">Sep 25 2020</div></div><div class="meta-panel__right-content"><div class="meta-panel__share"></div></div></div><h1 property="name">Radionuclide Imaging of Cardiac Amyloidosis and Sarcoidosis: Roles and Characteristics of Various Tracers</h1><div class="contributors"><span class="authors"><span class="heading">Authors</span>: <span role="list"><span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con1"><span property="givenName">Masatoshi</span> <span property="familyName">Hotta</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0001-6790-8804" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0001-6790-8804</a> <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection#a9c4c8dac8ddc6dac1c0c1c6ddddc8e9d0c8c1c6c687cac687c3d9" property="email" aria-label="Email address"><span class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="2b464a584a5f4458434243445f5f4a6b524a43444405484405415b">[email&#160;protected]</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con2"><span property="givenName">Ryogo</span> <span property="familyName">Minamimoto</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1026-255X" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1026-255X</a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con3"><span property="givenName">Toru</span> <span property="familyName">Awaya</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7154-3606" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7154-3606</a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con4"><span property="givenName">Michiaki</span> <span property="familyName">Hiroe</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con5"><span property="givenName">Osamu</span> <span property="familyName">Okazaki</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0001-6615-4713" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0001-6615-4713</a></span>, and <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con6"><span property="givenName">Yukio</span> <span property="familyName">Hiroi</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0001-5088-7656" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0001-5088-7656</a></span></span></span><a href="#tab-contributors" class="to-authors-affiliations" data-id="article-authors-viewall">Authors Info &amp; Affiliations</a></div><div class="core-self-citation"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span class="heading">Publication</span>: <span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">40</span></span><span class="delimiter">, </span><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">7</span></span></div><div class="doi"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020200068" property="sameAs">https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020200068</a></div></div><div class="info-panel"><div class="info-panel__left-content"><div class="info-panel__metrics info-panel__item"></div></div><div class="info-panel__right-content"><div class="info-panel__article_tools info-panel__item">



        
        <div class="article-tools"><a href="/personalize/addFavoritePublication?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068" target="_blank" class="article-tools__favorite btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Add to favorites"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-add-favorite"></i><span class="sr-only">Add to favorites</span></a><a href="/action/addCitationAlert?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068" target="_blank" class="article-tools__citation btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Track Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-alert-bell"></i><span class="sr-only">Track Citations</span></a></div>
</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Amyloidosis and sarcoidosis are systemic diseases that affect multiple organ systems. Accurate diagnosis of cardiac amyloidosis and sarcoidosis is particularly important because cardiac involvement can be fatal. Amyloidosis is characterized by the deposition of amyloid fibrils, and cardiac amyloidosis is classified into amyloid immunoglobulin light chain (AL) and amyloid transthyretin (ATTR) types. Radionuclide tracers for amyloidosis include <i>(a)</i> bone tracers, <i>(b)</i> amyloid-directed molecules, and <i>(c)</i> PET amyloid agents. Bone tracers are particularly sensitive in detection of ATTR type amyloidosis, whereas PET amyloid agents show a higher affinity for the AL type. In sarcoidosis, gallium 67 (<sup>67</sup>Ga) citrate scintigraphy and fluorine 18 (<sup>18</sup>F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) PET are pivotal to diagnosis of cardiac sarcoidosis, and <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT has particularly high efficacy in detection of sarcoidosis and monitoring of response to therapy. A major limitation of <sup>18</sup>F-FDG is physiologic uptake in the myocardium, which can remain in approximately 20% of patients even after elaborate preparation (eg, prolonged fasting &gt;12–18 hours, modification to a high-fat and low-carbohydrate diet, and injection of unfractionated heparin). This limitation has led to a search for potential new tracers. Recently introduced tracers that show promise include those used in somatostatin receptor imaging and cellular proliferation imaging, which provide detectability as high as that for <sup>18</sup>F-FDG without requiring dietary restrictions and have potential for monitoring disease activity.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200068">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200068">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Methodology of measuring the heart-to–contralateral chest ratio. 99mTc-PYP planar scintigram shows oval regions of interest over the heart and the contralateral lung to adjust for background. Mean measurements of uptake in the regions of interest are calculated, and the heart-to–contralateral chest ratio measurements are determined. The regions of interest are positioned to minimize overlap with sternal or focal rib uptake and maximize coverage of the heart without including the adjacent lung."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig1.jpeg" height="1792" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Methodology of measuring the heart-to–contralateral chest ratio. <sup>99m</sup>Tc-PYP planar scintigram shows oval regions of interest over the heart and the contralateral lung to adjust for background. Mean measurements of uptake in the regions of interest are calculated, and the heart-to–contralateral chest ratio measurements are determined. The regions of interest are positioned to minimize overlap with sternal or focal rib uptake and maximize coverage of the heart without including the adjacent lung.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Visual scoring on whole-body planar bone scintigrams (anterior-posterior view) acquired 3 hours after injection of 99mTc-DPD or HMDP. Cardiac uptake is compared with that of the surrounding ribs."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig2.jpeg" height="2289" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Visual scoring on whole-body planar bone scintigrams (anterior-posterior view) acquired 3 hours after injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-DPD or HMDP. Cardiac uptake is compared with that of the surrounding ribs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="ATTR cardiac amyloidosis in an 84-year-old man. Bone planar scintigram (a) of the left anterior oblique chest and SPECT/CT image (b) obtained 3 hours after injection of 99mTc-HMDP show myocardial uptake (circle in a) that is equal to rib uptake (grade 2), which is strongly suggestive of ATTR cardiac amyloidosis, and myocardial uptake predominantly in the septum (arrow in b), which indicates deposition of TTR."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig3a.jpeg" height="1307" width="1450" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. ATTR cardiac amyloidosis in an 84-year-old man. Bone planar scintigram <b>(a)</b> of the left anterior oblique chest and SPECT/CT image <b>(b)</b> obtained 3 hours after injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-HMDP show myocardial uptake (circle in <b>a</b>) that is equal to rib uptake (grade 2), which is strongly suggestive of ATTR cardiac amyloidosis, and myocardial uptake predominantly in the septum (arrow in <b>b</b>), which indicates deposition of TTR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="ATTR cardiac amyloidosis in an 84-year-old man. Bone planar scintigram (a) of the left anterior oblique chest and SPECT/CT image (b) obtained 3 hours after injection of 99mTc-HMDP show myocardial uptake (circle in a) that is equal to rib uptake (grade 2), which is strongly suggestive of ATTR cardiac amyloidosis, and myocardial uptake predominantly in the septum (arrow in b), which indicates deposition of TTR."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig3b.jpeg" height="1307" width="1501" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. ATTR cardiac amyloidosis in an 84-year-old man. Bone planar scintigram <b>(a)</b> of the left anterior oblique chest and SPECT/CT image <b>(b)</b> obtained 3 hours after injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-HMDP show myocardial uptake (circle in <b>a</b>) that is equal to rib uptake (grade 2), which is strongly suggestive of ATTR cardiac amyloidosis, and myocardial uptake predominantly in the septum (arrow in <b>b</b>), which indicates deposition of TTR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Whole-body 99mTc-aprotinin scintigraphy planar image in a healthy subject. Physiologic uptake is shown in the liver, spleen, and kidneys."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig4.jpeg" height="2291" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Whole-body <sup>99m</sup>Tc-aprotinin scintigraphy planar image in a healthy subject. Physiologic uptake is shown in the liver, spleen, and kidneys.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic" aria-label="ATTR cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man. (a) Late gadolinium–enhanced MR image shows subepicardial to transmural enhancement (arrows) in the basal myocardium. (b) 99mTc-aprotinin SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrows). (c) Left anterior oblique chest 99mTc-PYP planar scintigram shows uptake in the myocardium (arrow), which is suggestive of ATTR cardiac amyloidosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig5a.jpeg" height="1368" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. ATTR cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium–enhanced MR image shows subepicardial to transmural enhancement (arrows) in the basal myocardium. <b>(b)</b> <sup>99m</sup>Tc-aprotinin SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Left anterior oblique chest <sup>99m</sup>Tc-PYP planar scintigram shows uptake in the myocardium (arrow), which is suggestive of ATTR cardiac amyloidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="ATTR cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man. (a) Late gadolinium–enhanced MR image shows subepicardial to transmural enhancement (arrows) in the basal myocardium. (b) 99mTc-aprotinin SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrows). (c) Left anterior oblique chest 99mTc-PYP planar scintigram shows uptake in the myocardium (arrow), which is suggestive of ATTR cardiac amyloidosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig5b.jpeg" height="1290" width="1415" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. ATTR cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium–enhanced MR image shows subepicardial to transmural enhancement (arrows) in the basal myocardium. <b>(b)</b> <sup>99m</sup>Tc-aprotinin SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Left anterior oblique chest <sup>99m</sup>Tc-PYP planar scintigram shows uptake in the myocardium (arrow), which is suggestive of ATTR cardiac amyloidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic" aria-label="ATTR cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man. (a) Late gadolinium–enhanced MR image shows subepicardial to transmural enhancement (arrows) in the basal myocardium. (b) 99mTc-aprotinin SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrows). (c) Left anterior oblique chest 99mTc-PYP planar scintigram shows uptake in the myocardium (arrow), which is suggestive of ATTR cardiac amyloidosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig5c.jpeg" height="1290" width="1535" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. ATTR cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium–enhanced MR image shows subepicardial to transmural enhancement (arrows) in the basal myocardium. <b>(b)</b> <sup>99m</sup>Tc-aprotinin SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Left anterior oblique chest <sup>99m</sup>Tc-PYP planar scintigram shows uptake in the myocardium (arrow), which is suggestive of ATTR cardiac amyloidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="AL cardiac amyloidosis in a 72-year-old man. (a) Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows global transmural late gadolinium enhancement, which is suggestive of cardiac amyloidosis. (b, c) 11C-PiB PET/CT (b) and 99mTc-aprotinin SPECT/CT (c) images show diffuse uptake in the left myocardium, which indicates amyloid deposition."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig6a.jpeg" height="1383" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. AL cardiac amyloidosis in a 72-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows global transmural late gadolinium enhancement, which is suggestive of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(b, c)</b> <sup>11</sup>C-PiB PET/CT <b>(b)</b> and <sup>99m</sup>Tc-aprotinin SPECT/CT <b>(c)</b> images show diffuse uptake in the left myocardium, which indicates amyloid deposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="AL cardiac amyloidosis in a 72-year-old man. (a) Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows global transmural late gadolinium enhancement, which is suggestive of cardiac amyloidosis. (b, c) 11C-PiB PET/CT (b) and 99mTc-aprotinin SPECT/CT (c) images show diffuse uptake in the left myocardium, which indicates amyloid deposition."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig6b.jpeg" height="1296" width="1482" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. AL cardiac amyloidosis in a 72-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows global transmural late gadolinium enhancement, which is suggestive of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(b, c)</b> <sup>11</sup>C-PiB PET/CT <b>(b)</b> and <sup>99m</sup>Tc-aprotinin SPECT/CT <b>(c)</b> images show diffuse uptake in the left myocardium, which indicates amyloid deposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic" aria-label="AL cardiac amyloidosis in a 72-year-old man. (a) Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows global transmural late gadolinium enhancement, which is suggestive of cardiac amyloidosis. (b, c) 11C-PiB PET/CT (b) and 99mTc-aprotinin SPECT/CT (c) images show diffuse uptake in the left myocardium, which indicates amyloid deposition."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig6c.jpeg" height="1283" width="1468" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. AL cardiac amyloidosis in a 72-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows global transmural late gadolinium enhancement, which is suggestive of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(b, c)</b> <sup>11</sup>C-PiB PET/CT <b>(b)</b> and <sup>99m</sup>Tc-aprotinin SPECT/CT <b>(c)</b> images show diffuse uptake in the left myocardium, which indicates amyloid deposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 61-year-old woman. (a) Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows patchy enhancement (arrow) on the septal wall. (b) 18F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, indicating an active lesion. (c) 67Ga-citrate SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall that is similar to that in b."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig7a.jpeg" height="1217" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 61-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows patchy enhancement (arrow) on the septal wall. <b>(b)</b> <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, indicating an active lesion. <b>(c)</b> <sup>67</sup>Ga-citrate SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall that is similar to that in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 61-year-old woman. (a) Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows patchy enhancement (arrow) on the septal wall. (b) 18F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, indicating an active lesion. (c) 67Ga-citrate SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall that is similar to that in b."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig7b.jpeg" height="1146" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 61-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows patchy enhancement (arrow) on the septal wall. <b>(b)</b> <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, indicating an active lesion. <b>(c)</b> <sup>67</sup>Ga-citrate SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall that is similar to that in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 61-year-old woman. (a) Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows patchy enhancement (arrow) on the septal wall. (b) 18F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, indicating an active lesion. (c) 67Ga-citrate SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall that is similar to that in b."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig7c.jpeg" height="1146" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 61-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows patchy enhancement (arrow) on the septal wall. <b>(b)</b> <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, indicating an active lesion. <b>(c)</b> <sup>67</sup>Ga-citrate SPECT/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall that is similar to that in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 78-year-old woman. (a) Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows transmural enhancement (arrowheads) on the septal to anterior wall. (b) 18F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, suggesting active cardiac sarcoidosis. (c) 111In-pentetreotide SPECT/CT image similarly shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig8a.jpeg" height="1285" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 78-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows transmural enhancement (arrowheads) on the septal to anterior wall. <b>(b)</b> <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, suggesting active cardiac sarcoidosis. <b>(c)</b> <sup>111</sup>In-pentetreotide SPECT/CT image similarly shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 78-year-old woman. (a) Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows transmural enhancement (arrowheads) on the septal to anterior wall. (b) 18F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, suggesting active cardiac sarcoidosis. (c) 111In-pentetreotide SPECT/CT image similarly shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig8b.jpeg" height="1186" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 78-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows transmural enhancement (arrowheads) on the septal to anterior wall. <b>(b)</b> <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, suggesting active cardiac sarcoidosis. <b>(c)</b> <sup>111</sup>In-pentetreotide SPECT/CT image similarly shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 78-year-old woman. (a) Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows transmural enhancement (arrowheads) on the septal to anterior wall. (b) 18F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, suggesting active cardiac sarcoidosis. (c) 111In-pentetreotide SPECT/CT image similarly shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig8c.jpeg" height="1186" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 78-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows transmural enhancement (arrowheads) on the septal to anterior wall. <b>(b)</b> <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT image shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall, suggesting active cardiac sarcoidosis. <b>(c)</b> <sup>111</sup>In-pentetreotide SPECT/CT image similarly shows uptake (arrow) in the septal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image (a) shows patchy subepicardial enhancement (arrow in a) in the basal septum, where 118F-FDG PET/CT (arrow in b) and 11C-4DST PET/CT (arrow in c) images show uptake. These findings indicate cardiac sarcoidosis with activity. Because 11C-4DST is a cell proliferation imaging tracer, it accumulates predominantly in active lesions."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig9a.jpeg" height="1272" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image <b>(a)</b> shows patchy subepicardial enhancement (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the basal septum, where <sup>118</sup>F-FDG PET/CT (arrow in <b>b</b>) and <sup>11</sup>C-4DST PET/CT (arrow in <b>c</b>) images show uptake. These findings indicate cardiac sarcoidosis with activity. Because <sup>11</sup>C-4DST is a cell proliferation imaging tracer, it accumulates predominantly in active lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image (a) shows patchy subepicardial enhancement (arrow in a) in the basal septum, where 118F-FDG PET/CT (arrow in b) and 11C-4DST PET/CT (arrow in c) images show uptake. These findings indicate cardiac sarcoidosis with activity. Because 11C-4DST is a cell proliferation imaging tracer, it accumulates predominantly in active lesions."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig9b.jpeg" height="1250" width="1568" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image <b>(a)</b> shows patchy subepicardial enhancement (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the basal septum, where <sup>118</sup>F-FDG PET/CT (arrow in <b>b</b>) and <sup>11</sup>C-4DST PET/CT (arrow in <b>c</b>) images show uptake. These findings indicate cardiac sarcoidosis with activity. Because <sup>11</sup>C-4DST is a cell proliferation imaging tracer, it accumulates predominantly in active lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic" aria-label="Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image (a) shows patchy subepicardial enhancement (arrow in a) in the basal septum, where 118F-FDG PET/CT (arrow in b) and 11C-4DST PET/CT (arrow in c) images show uptake. These findings indicate cardiac sarcoidosis with activity. Because 11C-4DST is a cell proliferation imaging tracer, it accumulates predominantly in active lesions."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200068/asset/images/large/rg.2020200068.fig9c.jpeg" height="1250" width="1582" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Late gadolinium-enhanced MR image <b>(a)</b> shows patchy subepicardial enhancement (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the basal septum, where <sup>118</sup>F-FDG PET/CT (arrow in <b>b</b>) and <sup>11</sup>C-4DST PET/CT (arrow in <b>c</b>) images show uptake. These findings indicate cardiac sarcoidosis with activity. Because <sup>11</sup>C-4DST is a cell proliferation imaging tracer, it accumulates predominantly in active lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200068&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Dorbala S, Ando Y, Bokhari S, et al. ASNC/AHA/ASE/EANM/HFSA/ISA/SCMR/SNMMI expert consensus recommendations for multimodality imaging in cardiac amyloidosis: part 1 of 2—evidence base and standardized methods of imaging. <em>J Nucl Cardiol</em> 2019;2